english:
  title: A Colophon on the Casting of Metal Type
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the second month of spring in the first year of Yongle, the Prince addressed those around him, saying: "Whoever wishes to govern well must study broadly the classics and texts. Only then can one fathom all principles, rectify the heart, and achieve the fruits of self-cultivation, ordering of the household, good governance, and peace throughout the realm. Our Eastern land lies beyond the seas, and the books of the Middle Kingdom rarely reach us. Woodblock editions are easily damaged and worn. Moreover, it is impossible to carve and print all the books under heaven. I wish to cast type in bronze so that whenever we obtain a book, we may print from it and thereby spread its transmission far and wide—truly an endless benefit to all. Yet the expenses for this must not burden the people. I shall undertake this together with members of the royal house, meritorious officials, and all officers of goodwill. Thus may we succeed."

    Thereupon, funds from the royal treasury were fully expended, and commands were given to Officials Lee Jik, Lord of Yeoseong Min Mu-jil, Park Seok-myeong, and Right Counselor Lee Ying to oversee the work. Officials Kang Cheon-ju of the Military Provisions Bureau, Kim Jang-gan, Keeper of the Jangheung Treasury, Yu Yi of the Counselors' Secretariat, Kim Wi-min, and Park Yun-yeong, Compiler of the Imperial Academy, were appointed to direct the undertaking. The annotated texts of the Classics and the Spring and Autumn Annals from the royal library were used as the models for the type. From the nineteenth day of that month, the casting began, and within several months, the work had produced hundreds of thousands of characters.

    Humbly do we consider that our Prince possesses depths of wisdom and brilliance, virtue both cultured and illuminating. In the spare hours from ten thousand affairs of state, he has set his mind upon the Classics and Histories with unwearying diligence. He seeks to open the wellspring of good governance and illuminate the transformation of culture through writing. Thinking only of broadening moral education to illuminate the present age and transmit it to posterity, with steadfast devotion he has caused these characters to be cast and molded, so that multitudinous books might be printed—reaching ten thousand volumes and transmitting to ten thousand generations. With such grand designs and such far-reaching thought, the transmission of royal teaching and the eternity of sage rule shall surely endure together, growing ever more firm.
  footnotes:
    - The Prince addressed here is later known as King Sejong the Great of Joseon, who would become one of East Asia's most celebrated monarchs for his patronage of learning and creation of Hangul.
    - The 'first year of Yongle' refers to 1403 CE, during the reign of the Yongle Emperor of Ming China, when the Prince was still establishing his authority.
    - This colophon celebrates the creation of metal movable type (술주자), a technology that would enable mass production of books in Korea and become crucial to the nation's intellectual flourishing.
